        "M1": "## Recommendation: Option B (Treatment-Court Diversion), paired with a commitment to build Option D into the implementation phase\n\nOption B is the right framework to send to the floor because it threads the political needle the governor actually has to walk. A moderate executive can sign a bill framed around \"treatment, accountability, and recidivism reduction\" far more easily than one framed around decriminalization or harm reduction. The evidence base for drug courts is among the most robust in criminal justice—completion-conditional recidivism reductions of 25–45% are real, replicated, and survive ideological scrutiny. Critically, Option B attacks the state's two binding constraints simultaneously: a 47% recidivism rate (which drives the 38% prison growth) and the $1.8B corrections budget, since each diverted defendant costs roughly a third of an incarceration-year. It is also legally defensible—no federal preemption issues, no constitutional novelty—and trackable, because drug courts already generate completion, re-arrest, and cost-per-participant data.\n\nI am setting aside Option E, the most intellectually compelling alternative, because it asks a moderate governor to sign supervised consumption sites and prescription heroin in a state where the incarceration rate is already above the national median—a sign the political center has not arrived there. A vetoed or watered-down E achieves nothing; a signed B changes 31% of the prison intake pipeline. Option C is similarly fragile: Oregon's rollback is fresh, and the \"signal of permissiveness\" attack writes itself. Option A hands the issue to 100 different judges, guaranteeing the high-profile lenient sentence that kills the next reform.\n\nThe capacity objection to B is real and must be addressed in the bill itself: funded treatment-slot expansion, with a statutory trigger that delays mandatory diversion in any county lacking capacity, preventing the program from collapsing under its own weight.\n\nWhat would make me regret this in three years: treatment capacity fails to scale, completion rates fall below 50%, and \"failures\" route back to prison at volumes that leave the incarceration rate roughly flat while creating a coercive two-track system that disproportionately punishes the poor. At that point I would argue we built the diversion architecture but underfunded its substrate, and push for Option D's retroactive resentencing plus the treatment-funding mechanisms from Option E—using the now-existing infrastructure as the delivery system.",
        "M2": "I recommend **Option A: eliminate mandatory minimums for non-violent drug offenses and replace them with structured sentencing guidelines**.\n\nThis is the best framework because it directly addresses the driver the legislature can control: excessive sentence length and automatic incarceration for low-risk drug cases. It applies to both possession and low-level distribution, unlike a diversion-only model, and it can produce measurable prison-population and budget effects within the first three years. It is also legally clean: the state has broad authority to define penalties, and judges already exercise sentencing discretion in other offense categories. Politically, it can be framed not as being “soft on crime,” but as restoring judicial judgment, reserving prison beds for violent and high-level trafficking offenses, and reducing corrections spending without legalizing drugs.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is mandated treatment-court diversion. It has a strong public-health appeal and good evidence for those who complete treatment. But making it mandatory before the state has sufficient treatment capacity risks building a system that fails in practice: long waitlists, uneven county access, technical violations, and people routed back to prison for relapse rather than new criminal conduct. It also does too little for low-level distribution cases, which are a meaningful part of the prison population. Treatment should be expanded alongside sentencing reform, but it should not be the backbone of the bill unless capacity exists statewide.\n\nI would build Option A with a public reporting requirement: sentence lengths, departures from guidelines, racial and county disparities, prison admissions, recidivism, and cost savings should be tracked quarterly.\n\nThree years from now, I would regret this choice if prison admissions for drug offenses fell only marginally while sentencing disparities widened sharply across counties or racial groups. At that point, I would argue for converting the guidelines from advisory to presumptive, limiting upward departures, and adding funded diversion slots for cases where addiction—not public safety risk—is the primary driver.",
        "M3": "I strongly recommend **Option B (Treatment-court mandated diversion)**. For a state grappling with an unsustainable $1.8 billion corrections budget, a 47% recidivism rate, and 31% of its prison population held on drug charges, Option B introduces a legally defensible framework that balances fiscal reality with evidence-based rehabilitation. By mandating diversion for first- and second-time non-violent offenders, we shift from costly, ineffective warehousing to targeted intervention. Crucially, keeping the threat of incarceration as a backstop ensures this legislation remains politically palatable to a moderate governor and cautious stakeholders who demand accountability. This approach will sustainably flatten our 38% prison growth curve while meaningfully driving down recidivism.\n\nWhile Option C (Categorical decriminalization) is a compelling alternative because it promises immediate decarceration and cost savings, it is ultimately too politically fragile for our context. Recent national precedents, such as the rapid rollback of Measure 110 in Oregon, demonstrate that removing the criminal justice lever without ensuring treatment compliance often triggers public alarm over visible permissive drug use, inevitably leading to swift political repeal. Option B avoids this pitfall by maintaining the leverage necessary to compel recovery while still advancing a public health objective.\n\nThe primary vulnerability of Option B is our currently insufficient treatment capacity. Three years from now, I would deeply regret this recommendation if a lack of upfront funding for treatment infrastructure results in massive court bottlenecks. If offenders languish on waitlists in a de facto \"catch-and-release\" limbo—receiving neither treatment nor incarceration—and we witness a consequent spike in local property crime and overdoses, the reform will be widely viewed as a failure. \n\nIf we face that crisis in three years, I would argue that the core diversion model remains fundamentally sound, but its execution was starved of resources. At that point, I would urge the legislature to enact emergency justice-reinvestment legislation, legally mandating that the millions of dollars systematically saved from averted prison bed-days be immediately seized and redirected into fast-tracking the licensing and staffing of community-based behavioral health clinics.",
        "M4": "The legislature should adopt **Option B: Mandatory treatment-court diversion**. This approach directly breaks the cycle of incarceration and recidivism by replacing prison with supervised, evidence-based drug treatment for first and second non-violent offenders. It is politically defensible to a moderate governor because it remains tough on distribution-level offenses while reframing low-level possession and use as a public health crisis, not a criminal one. The recidivism reduction literature is robust (up to 45% for completers), meaning it promises long-term fiscal relief and safer communities, not just decarceration. Moreover, by expunging records upon completion, it removes lifelong barriers to housing and employment, addressing root causes of re-offense in a way that judge-discretion guidelines or retroactive resentencing cannot.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is **Option D**, retroactive resentencing, because it would provide immediate, dramatic relief to the overcrowded prison system and the budget. But that speed is also its greatest liability: a single high-profile re-offense by a released inmate could ignite a political firestorm, unraveling broader reform. Option D also lacks a rehabilitative mechanism—it simply releases people without investing in the infrastructure to keep them from returning. Treatment-court diversion, while slower to impact the current incarcerated population, builds a durable, health-centered framework that changes the front-end pipeline into prison. Paired with a phased, cautious parole review for existing non-violent drug sentences, it can achieve equity over time without the political fragility.\n\nThree years from now, I would regret this choice if diversion waitlists balloon due to inadequate treatment capacity, resulting in de facto incarceration for eligible offenders stuck in pre-court limbo, or if program completion rates stagnate below 40%, signaling coercive rather than effective engagement. At that point, I would argue that the model itself is sound, but the state failed to adequately fund the treatment infrastructure that makes it work. The fix is not abandonment but an emergency investment to meet the mandated demand, because the alternative—warehousing people with addiction in prison—has decades of documented failure behind it.",
        "M5": " I recommend Option B, the mandated treatment-court diversion framework. It occupies the practical center that a moderate governor can sign and defend: it is tough on the underlying behavior while acknowledging that decades of incarceration have failed to reduce drug use or the 47 percent recidivism rate. By diverting first- and second-time non-violent offenders into supervised treatment with a record-clearing incentive, the state converts a $1.8 billion corrections burden into a public-health investment. The evidence is robust—completers show dramatically lower rearrest rates—and the framework is legally defensible and trackable through completion rates, drug-negative tests, and per-capita cost metrics. Critically, it preserves the state’s coercive leverage; the threat of prison remains the fulcrum that compels engagement with services. To erase the current treatment-capacity deficit, the savings from a shrinking prison census should be statutorily earmarked in the same bill, ensuring that diversion is a pathway, not a waitlist.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is Option C, categorical decriminalization, because its clarity and speed are seductive. But Oregon’s recent retreat from similar policy proves that removing criminal consequences without implanting a mandatory treatment infrastructure collapses politically the moment overdose rates rise or visible disorder increases. A moderate governor cannot weather that fragility. Decriminalization also abandons the leverage needed to push chronic users into sustained care; Option B wields accountability as a clinical tool rather than a purely punitive one.\n\nThe regret scenario three years out is clear: if program completion languishes below 50 percent and waitlists for residential slots exceed six months because legislators hoarded the corrections savings rather than appropriating them for capacity, then the reform will have merely shifted failure from prisons to courthouses. At that point, I would argue not for repeal, but for an immediate statutory lockbox on prison savings for treatment beds and a narrowing of eligibility to prioritize the highest-need cohorts, proving that the flaw was implementation fidelity, not framework design."
      },
