      "element_summaries": {
        "E1": "**Recommendation: Option A (Densification along transit corridors)**\n\nFor a mid-sized city sustaining an aggressive 1.8% annual growth rate, the fundamental challenge is absorbing massive population increases without bankrupting the municipality or destroying its carbon budget. Option A is the only philosophy that aligns the city’s profound 18K-unit housing deficit with its tight €100M flexible capital budget. By upzoning transit corridors to allow 4-8 story mixed-use developments, the city leverages a free regulatory tool to crowd-in private capital for housing.",
        "E2": "**Recommendation: Option A – Densification along transit corridors**\n\nThe city must confront its housing deficit and climate mandate simultaneously, and corridor densification is the only philosophy that weds these two imperatives into a single, scalable investment logic. By permitting dense, mixed-use development within a 600-meter radius of transit stops and pairing it with aggressive tram/BRT expansion, you channel growth precisely where infrastructure capacity can be upgraded – fixing aging water mains, sewers, and power grids beneath the same streets – and where car-free living becomes th...",
        "E3": "# Recommendation: Option A — Densification along transit corridors\n\nChoose corridor densification. It is the only philosophy that simultaneously attacks the city's three binding constraints — an 18K-unit housing deficit, a 65% emissions cut, and a €100M flexible capital budget — with a single coherent spatial logic. Density along transit is how housing supply gets built at scale without sprawl, how per-capita emissions actually fall (transport is typically a third of urban emissions and is reduced only by changing where people live relative to where they go), and how infrastructure euros achie...",
        "E4": "**Adopt Option A: Densification along transit corridors**\n\nThe city should make corridor densification its north star. At 320,000 residents and growing, it is large enough to demand efficient infrastructure yet small enough that a single tram or BRT extension can reshape daily life for tens of thousands. Permitting 4–8 storey mixed-use development within 600 metres of transit stops converts the 18,000-unit housing deficit into climate-aligned growth: new residents gain low-emission mobility by default, while the historic centre and older suburbs remain intact, avoiding destructive clearance.",
        "E5": "I recommend **Option A: densification along transit corridors** as the city’s guiding philosophy—but with affordability and anti-displacement rules built into the corridor strategy from the start. This is the best fit because the city’s problems are interconnected: it needs more homes, lower emissions, upgraded infrastructure, and better access to opportunity under tight capital constraints. Transit-oriented densification gives the city a clear spatial logic for investment: put new housing, jobs, schools, clinics, and public space where public transport can carry the load."
