          "raw_content": "Triad 1:\nE1: Focuses on justice, rights, dignity, inequality (moral/spatial justice)\nE4: Focuses on expected value, constraints, efficiency, fiscal limits (optimization)\nE5: Focuses on systems, restructuring demand, regulatory leverage (structural/systemic)\n\nE1 and E5 share: Advocacy for 15-minute city/distributed urbanism, and both critique or avoid centralized, capital-heavy infrastructure bets. Both emphasize restructuring relationships (rights or systems) rather than optimizing within existing frameworks.\nE4: Supports centralized transit corridor densification, optimization approach.\n\nConstruct: Distributive justice/rights-based vs Technical optimization? Or ends-based vs means-based? \n\nActually, looking for bipolar construct: Perhaps \"Intrinsic dignity/rights vs Instrumental efficiency\"?\nOr \"Spatial justice as right vs Spatial efficiency as constraint\"?\n\nWait, E5 mentions \"regulatory leverage\" and \"restructuring systemic demand\" rather than individual rights. But it's still against the centralized model.\n\nAnother angle: E1 and E5 both emphasize the experience of daily life and dignity/quality of life, while E4 emphasizes macro constraints and aggregate outcomes.\n\nDimension: Lived experience/dignity vs Aggregate efficiency/optimization?\nE1: \"unequal distribution of time, health, and daily dignity\"\nE5: \"restructuring systemic demand\" (to improve conditions)\nE4: \"expected value\", \"binding constraints\", \"fiscal limits\"\n\nSo E1 and E5 are similar in prioritizing the restructuring of urban experience/demand/patterns over optimizing within constraints vs E4 which optimizes within constraints.\n\nLeft pole: Restructuring demand/experience/rights\nRight pole: Optimizing within constraints/efficiency\n\nBut that's specific to the content. Let me check Triad 2.\n\nTriad 2: E1, E2, E5\nE1: Justice/dignity\nE2: Geometry/movement\nE5: Systems/demand restructuring\n\nE2 and E5 both use systems/geometric/structural language (geometry of movement, systems perspective, restructuring demand) while E1 uses moral/rights language (spatial right, dignity, justice).\n\nConstruct: Structural/systemic causality vs Normative/ethical claims? Or Technical vs Moral?\n\nE2: \"geometry of how people move\" - technical/systemic\nE5: \"systems perspective\" - explicit systems\nE1: \"spatial right\", \"daily dignity\" - normative/rights\n\nYes: E2 and E5 share a systems/structural approach (focusing on patterns, geometry, systems) distinguishing them from E1's justice/rights approach.\n\nPoles: Systems/structural lo",
          "finish_reason": "unknown"
        }
      },
